This solution for Plus One works by simulating how we normally add 1 to a number by hand.
The digits of the number are stored in an array,
so the algorithm starts from the last index (rightmost digit) because addition always begins from the least significant digit.
It increases that digit by 1 and then uses % 10 to handle the carry.
If the digit becomes less than 10 after incrementing, the addition is complete and the updated array is returned immediately.
However, if the digit was 9, adding 1 makes it 10, so % 10 turns it into 0 and the carry moves to the next digit on the left.
The loop continues propagating this carry until a digit does not produce a carry. If all digits were 9 (for example [9,9,9]),
every digit becomes 0, meaning the number has increased in length (999 → 1000). In that case, the algorithm creates a new array of size n+1,
sets the first element to 1, and leaves the rest as 0.
